Previously, Dan Espen said:
>
> > >You can use FVWM as the window manager for GNOME if you want, but you're
> > >better off using something like Enlightenment because it understands GNOME
> > >management hints.  See www.enlightenment.org also.
> 
> Hmm...recruiting for E?

No, I like E in many ways, but it's just not as flexible as FVWM.  It's
also a lot more memory-hungry than FVWM.  I run FVWM (which is why I'm on
this list :-)  And of course, you /can/ use FVWM with GNOME if you choose
to do so (I did this for a long time).

However, FVWM can't do some things that make sense in the GNOME world.  For
instance, the GNOME pager won't work without a GNOME-compliant window
manager such as Enlightenment.  There are some other decoration hint type
of things also.  All in all it's not a big deal - but if you're talking
about Linux (which I think we were here) they're probably already installed
on the machine by default, so it isn't a big deal to load it up and give it
a try, in any case.  With a tiny bit of dot-file editing you can make GNOME
use fvwm or anything else (bb, sawmill, twm, etc).

FVWM is more flexible and lightweight which is why I use it.  And I have a
Sparc Ultra-II class system on my desktop, so I'm not strapped for
resources.  I just like my wm to not be sluggish (half the goal of a window
manager, IMHO, should be to become invisible so you barely even notice it's
there in the first place).

 -dan

